WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.440
For those of you who don't work in the pharmaceutical industry, what this, and indeed for those

00:00:12.440 --> 00:00:19.840
of you do, this diagram in front of you is essentially an org chart and it's also a timeline.

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:24.480
So this is how the biostatistics department at GSK is structured. I say it's like a timeline

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:28.480
because our structure essentially reflects the drug development life cycle. So this can

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:33.200
take up to 15 years, which is what this arrow at the bottom is presenting, and that takes

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:40.480
us through the research in vivo in vitro analysis all the way through to the clinical development.

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:46.439
And by and large, if you're not from industry or you are and that's familiar to you, you

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:52.840
can slice this up into two distinct ways of working really. The first is the sort of non-clinical

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:57.240
area, and that's actually where my group, Cisco Data Sciences, sits, but it's also where

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:02.520
our research statistics and our manufacturing statistics groups sit as well. And that's

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:07.199
a large group of statisticians, programmers, data scientists, around about 100 people.

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:11.760
But overwhelmingly, the vast majority of people in that group sit within the clinical space.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:16.279
And the clinical space has very, very different controls and ways of working to the non-clinical

00:01:16.279 --> 00:01:20.839
space. And it's the clinical space that we're going to be talking about today. So a team

00:01:20.839 --> 00:01:28.639
of 500 clinical data scientists, that we're going to call them. And I put data scientists

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:33.879
in quotes on this slide because, really, if you speak to anyone in that department, very

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:37.959
few people would actually call themselves a data scientist. They are made up of people

00:01:37.959 --> 00:01:41.519
whose job title is either statistician or programmer, generally.

00:01:41.519 --> 00:01:45.919
And one of the reasons why I think that I would also probably not call them data scientists

00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:53.040
in a sense is that, for me, a data scientist is someone who is multi-skilled in a number

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:57.080
of different ways. So they're not simply a statistician. They can code a bit as well.

00:01:57.080 --> 00:02:00.599
They can use different languages. They use the right tool for the job. And although there's

00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:07.320
a huge amount of talent in that 500 statisticians or programmers, at the start of our journey,

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:12.559
they weren't really data scientists in the sense that I'm describing.

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:17.119
Just to give you an idea of what kinds of skills we do have, away from just pure statistics

00:02:17.119 --> 00:02:22.399
and pure programming skill, I put up some proficiency, some rough estimates of proficiency

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:30.960
within the department at the start of this journey in 2018. And as you can see, the overwhelming

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:37.399
majority can program in SAS. I've said 99%. I put 100%. But I'm allowing myself a little

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:40.679
bit of room for one or two people who can't. But essentially, everybody can program in

00:02:40.679 --> 00:02:42.479
SAS.

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:47.520
There is some proficiency in R in the clinical space. But largely, R has been used historically

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:54.320
for the generation of graphics. And SAS still dominates in that area. It's normally bespoke

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:58.520
graphics that are particularly difficult to generate in SAS that R has been used for,

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:06.160
along with a few very proactive R users pushing R for graphics, and for clinical trial simulations

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:14.160
where R arguably lends itself better towards simulations. Python, again, I've tried to

00:03:14.160 --> 00:03:20.360
cover myself with 1%. Essentially, nobody's using Python in this clinical space. But just

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:24.759
in case, I put 1% there. And Julia, essentially, I've put up there to make it sound like I

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:31.720
know what I'm talking about. Essentially, no one is using that either.

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:39.639
So why are we not using R? Well, a lot of it comes down to the past 20 or 30 years of

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:46.919
drug development. And skills have been built up over that time in SAS. And alongside those

00:03:46.919 --> 00:03:51.639
skills, the tools we use, what are called SAS macros, which if you're not familiar with

00:03:51.639 --> 00:03:57.240
SAS would be akin to an R function. But you can think of all the functions and packages

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:01.639
you might build in R. All those kind of tools that we build to make our job easier have

00:04:01.639 --> 00:04:06.759
all been built in SAS. And in a clinical space, it's very, very heavily regulated.

00:04:06.759 --> 00:04:13.039
And so we have systems that control, to a very fine nature, our workflows that we use.

00:04:13.039 --> 00:04:18.640
And these systems, as well, are entirely built for SAS.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:22.920
Add all that to the fact that it's very conservative. The further along you get along the pipeline,

00:04:22.920 --> 00:04:29.799
the more conservative it gets within our industry. And you can start to see why R hasn't been

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:37.720
used. But the real one that I hear a lot is this statement here that regulators only accept

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:41.079
analyses performed in SAS. This is essentially a myth that has been around for a long time.

00:04:41.799 --> 00:04:47.160
It gets repeated in various different forms. And I've tried to give you an idea at the bottom

00:04:47.160 --> 00:04:51.480
of the slide as to what really that means and where that comes from, or at least where I think

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:56.760
it comes from. So you have, for example, when you're filing for submission with the FDA,

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:03.160
the Food and Drug Administration of America, you have to provide data sets in the SAS transport

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:08.200
format. And that's an open format. And this statement is, I'll put a link in the bottom

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:13.480
as to where that comes from. But this statement here is from the FDA. It's clearly an open

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:17.720
standard. I put a line of code, a bit of pseudocode on the right-hand side to highlight

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:22.119
just how easy that is to generate in R. In fact, there's less code in R than it would take in SAS,

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:28.839
ironically. But these kinds of things, these kinds of statements get put out there. And I

00:05:28.839 --> 00:05:33.720
think because it has SAS in it, there's always this assumption that SAS has to be used. And

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:37.000
where people aren't very, very close to the submission end of things, it's easy to see

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.959
how that gets changed and transformed over time. And people get very used to this SAS-dominated

00:05:41.959 --> 00:05:48.440
way of working. On the regulatory note, I could talk for an entire hour. I won't be,

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:55.399
but I could talk for an entire hour on this topic that Phil mentioned in the introduction.

00:05:55.399 --> 00:06:00.920
If you are interested in the regulatory barriers or perceived regulatory barriers that we face in

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:07.640
the pharmaceutical space, I would recommend you go to www.pharmaR.org. This is the R validation

00:06:07.640 --> 00:06:14.600
hub that Phil mentioned. And you can see here, in particular, our white paper on a risk-based

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:22.920
approach to package validation. So given all those barriers and challenges, why are we looking

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:29.239
at R now? I think one of the key reasons is the influx of new talent and skill around R coming

00:06:29.239 --> 00:06:37.399
from college, from university. And we may have people who have been using SAS for 20 or 30 years.

00:06:37.399 --> 00:06:43.079
But with this new people coming in with skills in R, generally, they're not coming out with skills

00:06:43.079 --> 00:06:47.880
in SAS. And what we're doing is, because no one else understands R very well, we're having to

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:54.200
retrain them. All their education has been in R. And we're retraining them in SAS to make them

00:06:55.239 --> 00:07:01.000
so that they can work with everybody else. And now, I think it's probably fair to say

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.600
that we've reached critical mass. We've got so many people who know what to use R that we're

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:08.920
now looking at it the other way around. Let's retrain some of the people that have been there

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:15.959
for 20 or 30 years in R. The other piece is the drive for innovation. And that's not new.

00:07:15.959 --> 00:07:19.640
We're always driving for innovation. But I think there's a few things, in particular, that I've

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:26.600
highlighted on this slide. The last two, the communication and visualization and the productivity

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:31.079
gains that I mentioned, I'll go through in a bit more detail in the next slide. For now, just to

00:07:31.079 --> 00:07:39.000
talk about the methodologies and simulation, what we're seeing is an increased drive to

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:47.640
use the latest statistical methodologies to try and design more efficient trials. And when I talk

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:52.760
about more efficient trials, what I mean is, if you think about a drug getting to market, up until

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:58.440
the point where you have proved the efficacy and the safety of that drug, your drug is something

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:05.399
that you want to expose as few people to as possible. It's a potentially dangerous compound

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:10.920
that we want to make sure that we're minimizing that exposure. So we need to reduce that. And

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:15.320
equally, if it is effective and it's safe, we want to get it to market as quickly as possible.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:21.640
And there's been a lot of investment in things like placebo reuse of data, BSK, and other

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:28.040
methodologies to try and create a more streamlined process for developing drugs. And a lot of that

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:32.280
requires heavy amounts of simulation. And there are a lot of tools that have been built around

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:36.119
that that are available in R. So they're really, really pushing things forward as well.

00:08:37.159 --> 00:08:42.359
Before I move on to the last two and I talk about visualization and the dynamic reporting aspect,

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:45.880
I just want to mention a couple of others that often get talked about in relation to

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:54.599
adoption of R. The first one being cost. I think cost is important in certain sectors.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:09:01.479
I wouldn't put it as important as any of the other things on this slide, actually.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:07.640
When you think about cost, yes, R is free and tools like SAS are not. But there's a huge cost

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:17.000
in training 500 people and updating all of our standard tools and systems and so on as well.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.159
So in a sense that the cost, yes, there's some long-term cost savings. But in the short term,

00:09:21.239 --> 00:09:28.039
actually, it's probably the other way around. And then the last one, the gateway to Python and

00:09:28.039 --> 00:09:33.640
open source, everything I'm talking about here with respect to R, you could switch out R and

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:41.400
put in Python or any other open source tool. R is being more statistical, I guess, in nature,

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:46.280
at least in its origins, compared to something like Python. It is a more natural language in

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:55.239
the pharmaceutical space to use. And that's why we've chosen it as the tool to sit alongside SAS.

00:09:55.239 --> 00:10:01.080
But certainly, once we prove the case for R, and if you go back to that validation point,

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:07.080
you can prove that case for R. Why not Python? Why not Julia? Why not other languages? Once you're

00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:11.400
in that open source space, you can start taking advantage of some of the interoperability between

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:19.400
these two tools. OK. So the two GSK Catholics I wanted to talk about, the first one is a shiny

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:29.239
use case. And this is something we call quantitative decision making at GSK. In a nutshell,

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:34.280
it is the probability of being able to make a decision at the end of the trial, given

00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:41.960
the operating characteristics of the study, so the study design, and various other pieces of

00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:46.200
information that we know up front. I don't want to talk through this in a lot of detail. Again,

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:53.239
this is something I have given a whole presentation on in the past. But essentially, what we try and

00:10:53.239 --> 00:10:58.280
do with quantitative decision making at GSK is we take known values. So up in the top right-hand

00:10:58.280 --> 00:11:02.440
corner, there's a diagram here where it talks about this is looking at treatment difference.

00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:06.520
So on the x-axis, you've got a difference, for example, a difference between our drug and

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:14.039
placebo, or our drug and some competitor on the market. And in a standard clinical trial,

00:11:14.039 --> 00:11:19.799
you might look at the difference between those two compounds. And you're going to generate some

00:11:19.799 --> 00:11:24.760
kind of p-value. And if it's a late phase study, you might be looking for something like p less

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:28.919
than 0.05 to show that there is some kind of treatment difference. And that's great at the

00:11:28.919 --> 00:11:34.840
study level. But what QDM is looking at really is the lifecycle of the compound. So in the early

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:47.719
phases of development, so in phase 2, where QDM is particularly used at GSK, you can't power study

00:11:47.719 --> 00:11:54.359
sufficiently to be able to make those p less than 0.05 kinds of statements. What you want to be

00:11:54.359 --> 00:11:59.960
able to do is, given everything you know about the drug, you want to be able to estimate

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:06.520
probabilities. What's the probability that the difference between our two compounds is greater

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:14.599
than some clinically meaningful, commercially viable difference? Now, all of this is quite

00:12:14.599 --> 00:12:20.760
complicated. It uses a Bayesian framework. We put priors on all the information we know. There's a

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:24.440
lot of study design elements that we consider. And what we're trying to get to at the end is

00:12:24.440 --> 00:12:28.679
the probability of success of the study. So the probability that we're going to be able to make a

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:35.719
clear decision as to whether to continue into the next phase of development or stop development of

00:12:35.719 --> 00:12:44.599
our compound. And because it's quite complicated, when we trained a lot of our clinicians in the

00:12:44.599 --> 00:12:49.000
methodology, they weren't immediately receptive to everything that we were saying. It's a lot

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:56.599
of complex mathematics when mathematics is generally not their first job. So

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:06.760
we developed an app. And in doing so, take all those factors, things like the sample size,

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:11.799
the randomization ratio, the standard deviation, things you can see on this screen here, hopefully.

00:13:11.799 --> 00:13:16.280
And you combine that with information about the minimum value and the target value,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.640
and potentially lots of other operating characteristics as well. And you allow

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:27.960
the clinicians and the clinical teams to play around with the sliders, change different options.

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:31.559
And then it starts to become real for them. They can start to see what the impact of the

00:13:31.559 --> 00:13:37.000
study design is on the ultimate probability of success. And that's really led, because this is

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.719
such an important initiative at GSK, it's rolled out across all of our studies at GSK that are in

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:53.239
that phase of development. And because of that, we're seeing widespread adoption of QDM methodology.

00:13:53.239 --> 00:13:57.479
Everyone is seeing the Shiny apps, and there's a huge number of requests for additional Shiny apps.

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:08.599
Second example, I'll go over this a little bit more briefly, is dynamic reporting. Essentially,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:13.080
our submission process at the moment, or our development process, is such that we generate

00:14:14.599 --> 00:14:25.400
summary datasets in a very old-fashioned, boring text tables format at the moment. And we generate

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:31.320
these in the same way we've done for 20 or 30 years. And that's fine for our submissions. But

00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:37.640
then when we want to present those in a PowerPoint presentation, and we want to publish those results

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:41.000
in some other way, what we find ourselves doing is reformatting all that information.

00:14:41.799 --> 00:14:46.359
Even, in fact, in the clinical study report, we hand over the data to our medical writing teams,

00:14:46.359 --> 00:14:51.880
and they end up doing things like manually merging columns and reformatting some of the data that

00:14:51.880 --> 00:14:59.080
we've given them before it goes to the clinical study report. So you could use, if you weren't

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:02.840
using Microsoft products, something like R Markdown would be equally suitable for this. We actually

00:15:02.840 --> 00:15:11.239
used the Officer package to prove this concept last year, that we could just take the summary

00:15:11.239 --> 00:15:17.239
datasets that we generate in Biostatistics and automatically place all of the outputs into

00:15:18.039 --> 00:15:23.799
each of these different formats without the need for huge amounts of transcription QC,

00:15:23.799 --> 00:15:30.440
which is what takes place today. So I hope that's given you a bit of an introduction.

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:36.039
And a couple of things that we're looking at that are really accelerating the adoption of R

00:15:36.039 --> 00:15:44.200
within GSK. What I want to move on to now is generally how we're trying to build this

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:49.960
capability. So I guess some of the marketing, some of the advertising that we've done internally to

00:15:49.960 --> 00:15:55.000
promote R. And in building capability, I've put out something here which will probably horrify

00:15:55.719 --> 00:15:59.159
anyone working in change management, but what I'm calling a simple recipe for

00:15:59.159 --> 00:16:06.119
building capability. Because the components here, the ingredients, if you like, in this recipe

00:16:06.119 --> 00:16:10.440
are not rocket science. It's more about how you do it. And that's what we'll talk about in the

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:15.400
rest of this webinar. So Tilo's going to talk about the environment that we've built, about

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:20.760
warp environment. And Michael will talk about the way that we're promoting on-the-job learning

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:25.400
through an initiative called R4QC. Before I move on to training, I just want to highlight as well

00:16:25.400 --> 00:16:30.039
that given this is a heavily regulated industry, processes and standards also plays a big part. We

00:16:30.039 --> 00:16:37.080
actually have standard operating procedures that effectively reference SAS directly. Not intentionally,

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:42.679
but our workflows are so built around the SAS workflow that certain elements that don't even

00:16:42.679 --> 00:16:50.440
make sense for R. And of course, marketing that I've mentioned. So let's move on, look at training

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:57.559
before I hand over to Tilo to talk you through the warp environment. What you can see on the

00:16:57.559 --> 00:17:04.359
slide now, which is a build slide, is three prongs of how we talk about data science within biostatistics.

00:17:04.359 --> 00:17:08.359
And this is largely based around our traditional roles. So at the top, we talk about modeling. And

00:17:08.359 --> 00:17:13.959
modeling is the role that's traditionally performed by a statistician in GSK biostatistics.

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:23.160
And a programmer would fulfill a data wrangling role within biostatics. The role that my team

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:28.520
fulfills in promoting R is more of an engineering role. And engineering can mean lots of different

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:33.239
things to lots of different people. What we mean in this space is things like building the

00:17:33.239 --> 00:17:41.160
environment, building applications, building R packages. So if you like the tooling that goes

00:17:41.479 --> 00:17:48.839
that helps support data science analyses. And the way we've gone about training everybody

00:17:48.839 --> 00:17:54.839
is to focus on the tidyverse and focus on ggplot2. So I've written these two things. ggplot2 is

00:17:54.839 --> 00:17:58.599
clearly part of the tidyverse. The reason I've separated them out in this diagram is because

00:17:58.599 --> 00:18:03.959
they are two separate face-to-face courses that we created, which are now virtual courses

00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:08.760
for everyone in biostatistics. And we want to make sure that everyone's got to a base level

00:18:08.760 --> 00:18:14.119
in tidyverse before we move on. We chose tidyverse because of all of the reasons you would

00:18:14.119 --> 00:18:19.000
normally choose tidyverse. So things like the simplicity of the functions, the consistency,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:24.520
and so on. But also because if you're trying to take people who know SAS and train them in R,

00:18:25.400 --> 00:18:31.000
R is a lot more expansive than SAS. It's a language. You have things like matrices and

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:37.239
lists and so on. And can get quite complicated when you get into it. SAS, on the other hand,

00:18:37.239 --> 00:18:42.839
is built around very simple flows, built around data steps. So we call data steps in SAS.

00:18:42.839 --> 00:18:47.880
And the way that that works is very, very similar to the way that the tidyverse is built around

00:18:48.599 --> 00:18:55.319
data frames or tibbles in the tidyverse vernacular. So that makes it a lot easier for someone coming

00:18:55.319 --> 00:18:59.160
across from SAS to R to pick up tibbles and pick up that way of working than it does.

00:18:59.719 --> 00:19:05.479
And in particular, the Magritte pipe and everything like that is very familiar to

00:19:05.479 --> 00:19:10.599
people coming from a SAS background. So we build them up in the foundations. And then in each of

00:19:10.599 --> 00:19:16.520
the core areas, we then look to strengthen core competencies. So we have bespoke training

00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:21.319
in various different forms. I put in the right-hand side some of the methods of delivery.

00:19:21.319 --> 00:19:26.520
So this will not all be face-to-face training. Lots of this is guidebooks, webinars, all sorts

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:31.479
of different things that we do to promote the learning. And there'll be core stats training

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:37.719
using real GSK data in programming. ProgPlus here represents sort of more targeted training

00:19:37.719 --> 00:19:41.880
in things like Stringer, Lubudate, those kind of packages for more advanced data manipulation.

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:44.439
And then we look at things like function writing from an engineering perspective.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:51.000
And then when the value comes in, it's around these kinds of things. So Shiny clearly plays

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:57.800
a big part of our future. So we've got some expansive targets around building Shiny capability.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:02.199
Publishing here, I'm using to refer to things like Officer, as well as R Markdown, Bookdown,

00:20:02.199 --> 00:20:08.599
Blogdown, those kinds of tools as well. And you can see that through this, we're building

00:20:08.599 --> 00:20:15.239
capabilities in each direction across the group. OK. In this particular section, what I'm going

00:20:15.239 --> 00:20:21.719
to focus on is the environment that we've built to support statisticians, programmers, and data

00:20:21.719 --> 00:20:27.640
scientists within biostatistics, and increasingly now beyond biostatistics as well. We call this

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:34.280
environment WARP because it's part of a wider initiative called SPACE. And if you want to make

00:20:34.280 --> 00:20:45.640
that into an acronym, we sometimes talk about the working area for our programming. OK.

00:20:45.880 --> 00:20:58.359
So as has been mentioned in the introduction, the majority of our users are clinical users,

00:20:58.359 --> 00:21:04.599
statisticians, and programmers. And the kind of data they work with, clinical trial data,

00:21:04.599 --> 00:21:13.079
is relatively small in the data science space. So a few hundred subjects visiting a clinic,

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:19.800
a handful of times, maybe less than 10 times, generating at most in some of our laboratory

00:21:19.800 --> 00:21:25.079
data sets a few megabytes of data. Certainly not generally in the gigabyte terms.

00:21:26.520 --> 00:21:33.800
And the kind of analyses that we're running are standard statistical models, linear models,

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:37.479
generalized linear models, mixed models, cross-proportional hazards, these kinds of things.

00:21:38.040 --> 00:21:45.160
And when we simulate that data, what we have is computationally demanding simulations where we

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:50.920
fit that model over and over again, as opposed to needing to work with very, very large data

00:21:50.920 --> 00:21:56.040
sources and trying to solve problems with memory and so on. The only exception to that is that we

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:03.079
are seeing increasing use of molecular and genomics data as well. And that's something

00:22:03.079 --> 00:22:08.920
that we'll have to adapt to and respond to in the future. So in terms of what that means our

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:12.119
environment needs to cover, well, we need an interactive environment at its core. And I'll

00:22:12.119 --> 00:22:17.079
talk through each of these components in the next few slides separately. We need a high performance

00:22:18.199 --> 00:22:24.760
capability to support those simulations that I mentioned. And with respect to our new

00:22:24.760 --> 00:22:27.319
capabilities, our shiny apps and our markdown-based

00:22:29.959 --> 00:22:35.000
workflows, we need an ability to share that kind of content.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:42.599
And of course, to do anything, we need access to all of our data sources.

00:22:43.239 --> 00:22:47.239
We've provided this through a centralized environment. That probably isn't a surprise

00:22:47.239 --> 00:22:51.719
to anyone who works in this industry. But our aim is to get people off desktops where we can

00:22:51.719 --> 00:22:54.760
and provide a level of consistency. Particularly in the clinical setting,

00:22:55.319 --> 00:23:01.160
we need consistency, traceability, transparency in what we do. And we have a large number of

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:06.280
users that we need to support when doing this. So we have capacity at the moment for around about

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:12.359
1,000 data scientists with 300 concurrent users, we estimate.

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:20.439
This diagram is just to highlight some of the technologies that are included in this environment.

00:23:21.079 --> 00:23:25.959
You'll see as well as R, you'll see technologies like Python and Stan mentioned. Generally,

00:23:25.959 --> 00:23:31.719
we access those through R as opposed to direct access through their own

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:40.199
IDEs. So everything is built around RStudio Server Pro, and it's very much designed as an

00:23:40.199 --> 00:23:48.199
R-based environment. All of those other components there are really just

00:23:49.160 --> 00:23:54.599
supporting the use of R. So even take something like Git and GitHub,

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:59.719
that's actually maintained completely separately, but we'll provide a connection

00:23:59.719 --> 00:24:05.640
in R to allow our code to be stored and managed through GitHub.

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:13.400
So we've chosen RStudio Server Pro. And again, maybe this is an obvious choice for many people,

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:23.560
but clearly the RStudio IDE is the standard IDE for R anyway. But increasingly in the data

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:30.280
science space, I do see a sort of a trend towards more notebook-like environments,

00:24:30.280 --> 00:24:35.160
but really in a clinical space, that doesn't work. We work with scripts primarily. And for those

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:41.479
users coming across from SAS, all they've ever known really is scripts. So first and foremost,

00:24:41.479 --> 00:24:50.839
we need an environment to be able to develop and execute scripts. And RStudio Server Pro is really

00:24:50.839 --> 00:24:57.239
nice in that it provides, well, the RStudio IDE generally provides notebook access and

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:04.040
obviously easy use of our markdown if you want it, and therefore is the best of both.

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:10.520
But it also provides the ability to load balance. So for us with a high number of users,

00:25:10.520 --> 00:25:18.359
we actually have two servers with RStudio Server Pro running. And users will log onto a single

00:25:19.319 --> 00:25:24.520
address, and they'll be put onto whichever server has the most capacity. And this is also really,

00:25:24.520 --> 00:25:28.520
really useful for things like maintenance to minimize the downtime that users experience as

00:25:28.520 --> 00:25:33.319
well. There are some challenges with the interactive environment, the load balancing

00:25:33.319 --> 00:25:37.319
with respect to high-performance usage, but I'll come onto that after the next slide.

00:25:37.880 --> 00:25:44.199
So in this slide, what I want to talk about is our means to manage such an environment. So

00:25:45.239 --> 00:25:51.640
for a regulatory environment, I suppose at the moment we are quite open. So we're not

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:57.640
locking much down for our users. First and foremost, we need to get people off laptops

00:25:57.640 --> 00:26:03.319
with R. And on a laptop, they're used to high levels of flexibility. So we provide a central

00:26:03.319 --> 00:26:11.479
installation of R, and that installation is updated every six months. So we have many,

00:26:11.479 --> 00:26:19.160
many versions of R, and all of the recent versions are exposed to users. So for every six months,

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:24.280
over a period of three years, you can go back and select a version of R that you want to use.

00:26:24.280 --> 00:26:28.359
And when we talk about a version of R, we don't just mean the core and recommended packages.

00:26:28.760 --> 00:26:35.160
To date, we currently have around 450 packages centrally installed in a system library as well.

00:26:35.160 --> 00:26:45.319
So when a new user logs onto the system, they get access to Tidyverse and other popular packages

00:26:45.319 --> 00:26:51.400
for our kind of work immediately. They don't have to go and install those packages. And moreover,

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:54.760
because these are centrally installed in the system library, everyone has the same version

00:26:55.000 --> 00:27:02.439
of those packages, which ensures a degree of stability and usage. We do allow flexibility,

00:27:02.439 --> 00:27:07.479
so users can install their own packages as well in their own personal user library. We're not

00:27:07.479 --> 00:27:12.119
restricting that at the moment, but it's very likely that we'll supplement this environment

00:27:12.119 --> 00:27:20.920
in the future with more static, stable versions of R that are a bit more locked down. The only

00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:25.319
element of control that we really have on the environment is provided through RStudio Package

00:27:25.319 --> 00:27:35.239
Manager. So RStudio Package Manager provides access to packages that users would typically

00:27:35.239 --> 00:27:41.719
go and install from CRAN, Bioconductor, GitHub, and so on. And with respect to CRAN and Bioconductor,

00:27:41.719 --> 00:27:45.560
we pretty much provide the whole of CRAN, or we do provide the whole of CRAN and Bioconductor.

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:53.160
For GitHub, users would have to request that particular repositories are added to our

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:57.239
environment before they can install it. So they can't directly access CRAN, Bioconductor, or

00:27:57.239 --> 00:28:03.319
GitHub, or anywhere else. And we also have our own GitHub enterprise, the GSK, as well, which we

00:28:04.359 --> 00:28:09.719
release packages onto, and users can use RStudio Package Manager to access those.

00:28:10.280 --> 00:28:14.280
What's actually really, really nice about RStudio Package Manager is that it allows us to monitor

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:20.199
the downloads. And so when we see users installing, many users installing the same package,

00:28:20.920 --> 00:28:26.199
what we can then do is to install that in the central system library in a future release.

00:28:27.479 --> 00:28:31.800
Again, just to limit the amount of personalization and customization that might affect

00:28:32.760 --> 00:28:39.640
the transferability of our code. And speaking of central monitoring, another really nice feature

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:49.319
that our admin support team use quite extensively is the admin screens that are available

00:28:50.359 --> 00:28:58.280
through RStudio, through RStudio Server Pro. So here you can see a view of our system.

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:04.920
What I haven't mentioned thus far is that the system, these two servers that we use are very,

00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:07.880
very powerful servers. They're originally intended for high-performance computing,

00:29:07.880 --> 00:29:12.760
so they each have 192 cores and three terabytes of RAM, which is why you can see sort of 1%

00:29:13.319 --> 00:29:20.119
CPU memory usage on here. So generally, we are not pushing these servers to their limits.

00:29:20.119 --> 00:29:25.719
What you can see, though, is these little spikes that occur here. And these spikes occur when a

00:29:25.719 --> 00:29:33.800
user tries to paralyze or does successfully paralyze code and executes that in the background.

00:29:34.439 --> 00:29:41.000
So we can monitor the system, see these spikes, and then talk to those users. Users are permitted

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:46.359
to generate, you know, they are allowed to paralyze code and they are allowed to practice

00:29:46.359 --> 00:29:52.520
HPC runs, but our expectation is that they run them on a separate HPC system, which I'll talk

00:29:52.520 --> 00:30:01.079
through next. So that system is fully accessible from our RStudio Server Pro environment.

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:12.359
So we built an add-in to access Slurm, which is the tool that we use for accessing HPC.

00:30:12.359 --> 00:30:17.800
So you can see on here, each one of these is a different server. So when the users in RStudio

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:23.800
Server Pro access that add-in, the information they enter there essentially writes the necessary

00:30:23.800 --> 00:30:32.839
script to launch that job on to two separate HPC nodes. Again, all of these nodes, every single

00:30:32.839 --> 00:30:38.920
one of these servers in this diagram has 193 terabytes of memory, which is far too much for

00:30:38.920 --> 00:30:44.439
our management node. It doesn't need anything like that. And no doubt, we'll change that in

00:30:44.439 --> 00:30:49.880
the future. But certainly for the HPC, that means we've got some very powerful servers available.

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:56.359
One point to note, I mentioned that we built an add-in for this. We were sort of bleeding edge

00:30:56.359 --> 00:31:02.280
when we were doing this and the functionality wasn't readily available in RStudio.

00:31:03.640 --> 00:31:10.760
I understand that it is available now. You can use Launcher within RStudio to work with Slurm as

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:20.760
well as Kubernetes. But until GSK migrates to start using Kubernetes, we are still using our

00:31:20.760 --> 00:31:31.719
own custom add-in at this moment in time. So beyond the obvious, I just want to now highlight

00:31:32.760 --> 00:31:37.000
the value add, I guess, of this environment. So the new things that we can do now that we

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:44.359
couldn't already do in our SAS-based environments. And for content sharing, so for sharing

00:31:45.479 --> 00:31:54.359
Shiny apps, RMarkdown documents, Bookdown, Blogdown, we use RStudio Connect.

00:31:55.560 --> 00:32:00.680
We have one server at the moment running RStudio Connect. In the future, again, that might be two.

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:05.800
So we might evolve to have a development and production server. But at the moment,

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:11.319
it's all in one and it's a pretty liberal model. So users can publish anything they like. So you

00:32:11.319 --> 00:32:18.760
see a lot of apps, development apps with the word test next to them. Primarily, I'd say the Shiny

00:32:18.760 --> 00:32:23.800
apps are, I mean, the Shiny apps are a mixed bag. We get all sorts of QDM, quantitative decision

00:32:23.800 --> 00:32:29.719
making app that I mentioned earlier. We get various dashboards that people have created,

00:32:30.359 --> 00:32:36.839
training apps, and so on. The image in the left-hand side is taken from a proof of concept

00:32:36.839 --> 00:32:47.560
we did to use Shiny to report clinical trial data. So we've got an ongoing initiative at the moment

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:52.760
where we're looking at replacing a lot of our standard outputs with a Shiny app. And there's

00:32:52.760 --> 00:33:01.640
a lot of questions that come with that around things like data access and what to do if we

00:33:01.640 --> 00:33:06.119
find anything in there when we're exploring the data, how do we report that and so on.

00:33:06.119 --> 00:33:09.479
So there's a lot of questions of that, but we're starting to explore Shiny for that as well.

00:33:10.920 --> 00:33:17.560
Otherwise, we also use RStudio Connect for all of our training materials. So most of those are

00:33:17.560 --> 00:33:22.680
produced using Bookdown and we host those on Connect. One particular feature I want to highlight

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:27.000
that isn't mentioned on this slide, but is something that I really, I'm really, really

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:33.800
thrilled about is there's a feature in RStudio Connect that allows you to publish directly from

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:41.959
Git. So we use Git and GitHub extensively, particularly within my team. And you can

00:33:41.959 --> 00:33:49.400
point RStudio Connect directly at a particular branch on GitHub. So for example, we'd have our

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:58.199
production apps pointing at the master branch and we'll have a test branch where we would

00:33:58.199 --> 00:34:06.040
point RStudio Connect at for more regular updates and testing. And that's a really,

00:34:06.040 --> 00:34:09.479
really nice feature that often doesn't get talked about that I just wanted to highlight.

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:16.520
Otherwise, I think RStudio Connect generally works really, really well for us. The only

00:34:16.520 --> 00:34:22.520
bit of guidance that we often need to work with our users on is around data access. So

00:34:23.239 --> 00:34:28.040
sometimes people don't understand how RStudio Connect runs. So you can basically configure it

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:34.439
to run as you as the user that's trying to access that content, or you can configure it to run as a

00:34:35.399 --> 00:34:40.520
generic user. And that affects things like data access. And so we're often having to work with

00:34:40.520 --> 00:34:47.479
users to explain that. Equally, you can configure, you can design an app such that the data is

00:34:47.479 --> 00:34:52.120
deployed as part of the app, or you can write apps to access external data sources where

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:58.040
some of what I just mentioned becomes more of an issue. But there's lots of different mechanisms

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:03.639
for controlling access within Connect. And that's one of the key advantages, I think,

00:35:03.639 --> 00:35:09.399
that we see for it for Shiny apps, is making sure that the right people see the right content.

00:35:11.959 --> 00:35:15.560
Just before I round off, I just wanted to mention some of the back ends. I've mentioned things like

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:24.840
relational databases. These are ideal for clinical trial data. Our clinical trial data is actually

00:35:24.840 --> 00:35:29.320
stored on file shares at the moment. But in future, it'll either live on a relational database

00:35:29.320 --> 00:35:34.600
or a graph database. So we've provided access to a number of internal file shares, and

00:35:35.479 --> 00:35:42.520
we're able to access relational databases as well. And at the bottom of the slide is mentioned

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:49.000
Hadoop clusters. Outside of a sort of clinical setting, there are a number of users who want

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:55.399
to access things like real world data, electronic health record databases that are stored on

00:35:55.399 --> 00:35:59.959
separate Hadoop clusters within GSK. So we provide access to those. And then the second

00:35:59.959 --> 00:36:05.560
one down on the slide, the object store that we have. Again, something that's perhaps not talked

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:15.320
about too much these days, but I think we will see it a little bit more in the future, is the

00:36:15.320 --> 00:36:21.320
concept of an object store for data. And we have some fairly large structured and unstructured

00:36:21.320 --> 00:36:27.239
data sources that we access through the object store. And it's something that's helped us develop

00:36:27.239 --> 00:36:34.840
our first clinical RNA sequencing pipeline, which we'll be able to announce later this year,

00:36:35.560 --> 00:36:43.959
as well as providing a means to enable another pipeline that allowed us to

00:36:44.919 --> 00:36:53.320
analyze COVID-19 data and respond to a demand from our clinical operations

00:36:53.959 --> 00:37:00.199
group to try and understand what the impact of COVID-19 is going to be on clinical trial

00:37:00.199 --> 00:37:04.679
recruitment. So there's been a couple of really nice use cases where connecting to the object

00:37:04.679 --> 00:37:09.159
store has been particularly powerful. And we're very grateful for the work that's gone into

00:37:09.159 --> 00:37:15.879
getting AWS S3 back onto CRAN. So I'll just finish with an overview of the whole system.

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:21.080
I've spoken about each of these components. The only one really to highlight that I haven't

00:37:21.080 --> 00:37:26.760
mentioned before is this management. I haven't mentioned in any detail is this management node.

00:37:26.760 --> 00:37:32.520
So this contains our centralized R distribution. So whether it's Connect, whether it's

00:37:32.520 --> 00:37:36.199
Interactive Environments or HPC nodes, all of these are working off the same base

00:37:36.840 --> 00:37:42.199
R installation, which sits on there, as well as things like our Studio Package Manager,

00:37:42.199 --> 00:37:47.479
then to manage that, and the Slurm workload manager. So having this extra node independent

00:37:47.479 --> 00:37:52.520
from the rest is kind of useful. It's not necessary as such to have it as a separate node.

00:37:52.520 --> 00:37:55.959
And as I mentioned in the previous slide, it's a little bit overpowered at the moment

00:37:56.679 --> 00:38:00.520
for what we need it for, but it's a really, really useful component, as well as the load

00:38:00.520 --> 00:38:06.760
balancing that takes place everywhere else. And as mentioned, a future improvement will be to

00:38:07.639 --> 00:38:11.800
balance the content across the Connect services, as well.

00:38:14.600 --> 00:38:22.600
So with that, I will round off and hand over to Michael to talk about our on-the-job learning,

00:38:22.600 --> 00:38:28.600
so an initiative called R4QC, in particular. Thank you very much.

00:38:28.679 --> 00:38:33.399
Yeah, my name is Michael Rimler. I am in clinical programming within GSK Biostatistics,

00:38:33.399 --> 00:38:41.320
and I am here to talk about our adoption story, or our adoption story, within clinical programming,

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:48.679
and really in the clinical reporting process. The objectives of this project really are kind

00:38:48.679 --> 00:38:55.719
of twofold at a top level. One is driving capability. So as Andy mentioned, we have

00:38:56.360 --> 00:39:04.040
a vast majority of our staff are historically SAS programmers, but we're moving into this

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:08.120
space where we want to integrate R into the clinical reporting process. And to do that,

00:39:08.120 --> 00:39:12.439
we need that capability. We need people to be able to program in R. And although people have

00:39:13.560 --> 00:39:19.399
developed their SAS skills over time, I've been in the industry for 10, 11 years now,

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:26.520
and virtually everything that I've learned in terms of SAS has been on the job,

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:31.719
where I had a challenge that I needed to figure out how to resolve, and I asked questions,

00:39:31.719 --> 00:39:36.919
I looked things up, and I figured out it wasn't from sitting in classes and taking courses and

00:39:36.919 --> 00:39:43.719
working on problem sets and things like that. And so we want to be able to build that capability.

00:39:43.719 --> 00:39:47.560
And secondly, we want to establish an environment. And by environment, I don't mean what Tilo's

00:39:47.560 --> 00:39:52.840
saying, environment, although that, of course, is very, very important, but really making sure

00:39:52.840 --> 00:39:58.679
that people have the right to, the permission to engage in certain activities in the clinical

00:39:58.679 --> 00:40:04.600
reporting process. We know what the ways of working are, things like that, so that someone

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:09.320
comes in and then has the tools available to them to do that as well. So someone comes in

00:40:10.280 --> 00:40:15.159
and we hire them in, and apples to apples, they look the same as a newly hired SAS programmer,

00:40:15.159 --> 00:40:20.760
but they happen to know R, as Andy mentioned, that this is where a lot of the folks coming out

00:40:20.760 --> 00:40:26.679
of university are coming in with, that they can be just as productive, they don't have to

00:40:26.679 --> 00:40:31.479
go through additional steps of learning, additional training, so that they can be productive,

00:40:31.479 --> 00:40:36.439
they can be productive right out of the gate. Along this process, we've been asking questions

00:40:36.439 --> 00:40:40.760
like, well, why are we doing this? What's the role of R versus SAS in our future? And to Andy's point,

00:40:41.159 --> 00:40:46.520
that also brings into account more open source, but here we're focusing on R. So what is the

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:52.520
role of R versus SAS? Now, my perspective in leading this project, and I feel like I have

00:40:52.520 --> 00:40:59.080
the support of our senior management, is that it's integrating R and SAS. It's not about flipping a

00:40:59.080 --> 00:41:05.080
switch and doing R or SAS, it's about how do we integrate this into our processes? How are we

00:41:05.080 --> 00:41:09.800
doing this? What are the elements that are needed to declare our teams to be R-ready? And what's

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:16.199
next? So SAS has a certain amount of capabilities, other languages have certain things that they

00:41:16.199 --> 00:41:20.679
excel at, but the fact that we're trying to integrate R into our processes, does that open

00:41:20.679 --> 00:41:26.600
up the door for our department to be delivering other things to our quote-unquote customers

00:41:27.479 --> 00:41:34.919
beyond our conventional data sets, tables, listings, and figures? This started with a project

00:41:34.919 --> 00:41:43.879
that was called R for QC, where we wanted to look at using R for the QC process. So for those that

00:41:43.879 --> 00:41:51.560
are unfamiliar with a somewhat conventional QC process within clinical reporting, you have a

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:55.560
production-side programmer who creates the output, they create the data set, they create the table,

00:41:55.560 --> 00:42:00.919
that sort of thing. And then someone else, an independent programmer, independently creates code

00:42:00.919 --> 00:42:05.000
using the same inputs, but then a different process, because independently generated. And if

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:09.639
they get the same outcome at the end, then that satisfies a significant level of the requirements

00:42:09.639 --> 00:42:15.239
from a validation perspective. And so that's what we were looking at when the R for QC project,

00:42:15.239 --> 00:42:21.080
in parts one and two, we focused on displays, just looking at, not looking at data sets,

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:26.280
and it was more of a proof of feasibility, proof of concept type model. We only did about nine

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:33.879
displays in part one, and then we expanded the team and expanded, and actually in part two, we

00:42:34.760 --> 00:42:47.719
were able to replicate or doubly validate and compare to the production-side SAS-generated

00:42:47.719 --> 00:42:54.120
displays using R as opposed to SAS. It was about 150-some displays that were in that proof of

00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:59.879
concept. That opened the door for our part three, where we sort of go live, which was one of our

